{{wikipedia}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|attencioun}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|attentio|lang=la}}, from {{term|attendere}}, past participle {{term|attentus||to attend, give heed to}}; see [[attend]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/əˈtɛn.ʃən/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/@"tEn.S@n/}}
* {{audio|en-us-attention.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|s}}

# {{uncountable}} [[mental|Mental]] [[focus]].
#: ''Please direct your '''attention''' to the following words.''
# {{countable}} An [[action]] or [[remark]] expressing [[concern]] for or [[interest]] in someone or something, especially [[romantic]] interest.
#* '''1818''', [[w:Mary Wollstonecraft Shelley|Mary Wollstonecraft Shelley]], ''Frankenstein; or, the Modern Prometheus'', ch. 3,
#*: She attended her sickbed; her watchful '''attentions''' triumphed over the malignity of the distemper.
#* '''1910''', [[w:Stephen Leacock|Stephen Leacock]], "How to Avoid Getting Married," in ''Literary Lapses'',
#*: For some time past I have been the recipient of very marked '''attentions''' from a young lady.
# {{uncountable|military}} A state of [[alertness]] in the [[standing]] position.
#: ''The company will now come to '''attention'''.''

